olidated through a number of case studies that offer analyses of a range of television drama texts including ‘Ally McBeal', 'Supply and Demand', 'The Bill', 'Second Generation', 'Star Trek: Enterprise', 'Queer as Folk', 'Metrosexuality' and 'The Murder of Stephen Lawrence'.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMulticulturalismxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitics. 0aTelevision plays, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevision plays, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aTelevision. 4aFilm and Media Studies 2021. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Television / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aMarxist-socialism.  aaesthetics.  aanti-racism.  afeminism.  apolitics of identity.  apostmodernism.  aprogress.  aprogressiveness.  asubaltern identity categories.  atelevision drama.1 aHarris, Geraldine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779172640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847791726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847791726/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles